parameters: \pop[2]Everyone seems to be getting along, as I head back to the group.
\pop[2]Klace slowly sips on his glass of wine, and everybody mingles with each other.

\pop[3]Welcome back! Was starting to worry you'd ditch us.

\pop[4]No hard feelings if that's the case, of course.
Isaac planned this night just for you, remember?

\pop[4]Yeah. I save it for the people who are worth it.

\pop[3]Yeah. Public scene, big uproar, obstructing paths?

Pestering a public figure can net you like ten different penalties.
\pop[4]Really? And that's been set in stone?
That's not just one of the glitches happening lately?

Trust me, I've heard every possible theory about \c[23]Argus\c[0].
The world was dealt a bad hand, and they just wanted to help. That's all.
\pop[4]You should hear what some of the people say to me at work.

\pop[3]Well, I mean we're not just giving them money.
We're giving them the freedom to control our lives.
I know it's for the greater good, but it's still strict.
\pop[4]You can still do whatever you want, though. You're not tied down.
At the end of the day, you're still in control of your score.
\pop[3]Yeah, but there's a lot of incentive to be an obedient drone.
A bad score can literally destroy your life \c[14]and\c[0] your social status.
Especially with all the partying I do on tour.
Tank your score, and they still let you buy out a bar?
If any normal person tried that, they'd just be laughed away.
\pop[3]So the scores aren't as absolute as we think.
I mean, as far as theories go, that's pretty common.
\pop[4]But you can't say that's part of \c[23]Argus\c[0]' game.
Notable people have always been given special treatment.
It's not like that's a new addition to our society. Nothing changed.
\pop[4]That's a bit too deep for me.
No sense wasting time on something you can't change.
It's just wishful thinking -- like trying to defy your vision.
\pop[3]That doesn't mean you should just sit back and give up.
As long as you believe in your cause, a losing battle can still be worth fighting.
\pop[4]You guys flip-flop way too much on whether or not you believe your visions.
\pop[4]Us and the rest of the world, Isaac.
We weren't all given a bright one like you were.
\pop[2]I know alcohol was at play, but Dante just made a big mistake.
\pop[2]Revealing facts about another person's vision? Really bad move.
\pop[2]I didn't have a vision, but I knew that they were super intimate.
\pop[2]Sharing your vision with someone else was an expression of trust.
\pop[2]To have them speak about it to others? It was a bit of a betrayal.
\pop[4]You may think it's bright, from what I told you.
But unless you're all there beside me, it'll feel hollow.
When things get tough, the hope that I can change it keeps me going.
\pop[2]Dante shakes his head, upon realizing his mistake.
I didn't mean to speak for you.
I would trust all of you with this stuff. Just not now.
\pop[4]That's fair. Anyway, let's go back to Taylor.
You've heard every theory? What are some of the worst?
Whenever something weird happens, people on the internet will say aliens.
And I do have to admit -- \c[17]Komorebi\c[0] is pretty high up there on the weird scale.
\pop[3]Hey, I never said I believed it.
I think the deterrent theory is way better.
\pop[4]Oh! I know about that one, actually.
Right before the first visions, world tensions were high.
Everyone thought we were moments away from all-out war.
\pop[4]Then all of a sudden, \c[17]Komorebi\c[0] steps in.
We don't care about fighting each other anymore.
We have a new common enemy. The future.
It's not something you can take, like a nation.

Whether random, or created -- that's still the case.
\pop[3]I don't think I can buy the theory that someone created \c[17]Komorebi\c[0].

\pop[4]Yeah, they're always up to something over there.
I know they were obsessed with contacting another universe for a while.
\pop[4]I don't think we were worthy of a response.
Like Taylor joked about, this is probably just the darkest timeline.
They take one look at what we have to put up with, and run the other way.
\pop[2]Taylor holds up a bottle of booze, implying that it's time to drink more.
\pop[3]Besides, it's a waste of time to focus on questions that have no answer.
Like, why do scissors come in packages that require scissors to open?
I'm buying a pair! That obviously means that I don't have one to use.
\pop[4]Why don't you just use a kitchen knife to open it?
\pop[4]We have like, ten knives in the kitchen drawer.
You \c[14]do\c[0] know that you don't need to use scissors, right?
\pop[3]But there's a little picture of scissors next to the dotted line...
\pop[3]Is it okay if I just start drinking again...?
I mean, we're here to have fun, not rip into Taylor.
But I do appreciate talking about more "real" issues.
Even if we'll never know the truth, it's still healthy to talk about.
It can't be all fun and games, even if we want it to be.
Honestly, this is one of the best nights I've ever had.
\pop[3]You must not have much freedom when you're on tour.
\pop[3]Nah. I'm always at arm's length for one person or another.
But I told them I wanted to be left alone while I'm on this hiatus.
At least it'll give me the chance to prove that I can care for myself.
\pop[4]And even if you couldn't, we'd be there for you.
How about we grab some bottles and head back to my place?
Just remember what I said about taking the back door.
\pop[3]Didn't know you guys had that kind of relationship~
\pop[2]A moment later, we all scurry toward the bar.
\pop[2]I grab a few bottles of whatever stands out to me.
\pop[2]"Like a kid in a candy store", is a pretty apt expression.
\pop[2]Especially for Taylor, who seems overwhelmed by the possibilities.
\pop[2]He keeps taking a bottle, putting it back, and then taking another one.
